# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sitemap-xml
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sitemap-xml/glossary-seo] Search engines crawl the web, following links from page to page, and index the content found.
[src:sitemap-xml/glossary-seo] When you search, the search engine displays the indexed content.
[src:sitemap-xml/glossary-seo] If you follow those rules closely when doing SEO for a website, you give the site the best chances of showing up among the first results, increasing traffic and possibly revenue (for e-commerce and ads).
[src:sitemap-xml/glossary-seo] Search engines give some guidelines for SEO, but big search engines keep result ranking as a trade secret.
[src:sitemap-xml/glossary-seo] SEO combines official search engine guidelines, empirical knowledge, and theoretical knowledge from science papers or patents.
[src:sitemap-xml/glossary-seo] When exploring the website, crawlers should only find the content you want indexed.
[src:sitemap-xml/glossary-seo] Write content using your visitors' vocabulary.
[src:sitemap-xml/glossary-seo] Use text as well as images so that crawlers can understand the subject.
[src:sitemap-xml/glossary-seo] You get most traffic when other established sites link to your site.
[src:sitemap-xml/google-search-console] Until 20 May 2015, the service was called Google Webmaster Tools.
[src:sitemap-xml/google-search-console] In January 2018, Google introduced a new version of the search console, with changes to the user interface.
[src:sitemap-xml/google-search-console] In September 2019, old Search Console reports, including the home and dashboard pages, were removed.
[src:sitemap-xml/google-search-console] Since 2019, Search Console has supported Domain properties, which combine all protocol and subdomain variations (such as http, https, www, and non-www) into a single property, simplifying site management and reporting.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] A **site map** or **sitemap** is a list of pages of a web site within a domain.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Sitemaps may be addressed to users or to software.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Many sites have user-visible sitemaps which present a systematic view, typically hierarchical, of the site.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] These are intended to help visitors find specific pages, and can also be used by crawlers.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] They also act as a navigation aid by providing an overview of a site's content at a single glance.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Alphabetically organized sitemaps, sometimes called site indexes, are a different approach.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] For use by search engines and other crawlers, there is a structured format, the XML Sitemap, which lists the pages in a site, their relative importance, and how often they are updated.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] This is pointed to from the robots.txt file and is typically called **sitemap.xml**.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] The structured format is particularly important for websites which include pages that are not accessible through links from other pages, but only through the site's search tools or by dynamic construction of URLs in JavaScript.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Google introduced the Sitemap protocol, so web developers can publish lists of links from across their sites.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] The basic premise is that some sites have a large number of dynamic pages that are only available through the use of forms and user entries.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] The Sitemap files contain URLs to these pages so that web crawlers can find them.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Bing, Google, Yahoo and Ask now jointly support the Sitemaps protocol.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Since the major search engines use the same protocol, having a Sitemap lets them have the updated page information.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Sitemaps do not guarantee all links will be crawled, and being crawled does not guarantee indexing.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Google Webmaster Tools allow a website owner to upload a sitemap that Google will crawl, or they can accomplish the same thing with the robots.txt file.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Below is an example of a validated XML sitemap for a simple three-page website.
[src:sitemap-xml/site-map] Sitemaps are a useful tool for making sites searchable, particularly those written in non-HTML languages.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Google first introduced Sitemaps 0.84 in June 2005 so web developers could publish lists of links from across their sites.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Google, Yahoo! and Microsoft announced joint support for the Sitemaps protocol in November 2006.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] The schema version was changed to "Sitemap 0.90", but no other changes were made.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] In April 2007, Ask.com and IBM announced support for Sitemaps.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Also, Google, Yahoo, MSN announced auto-discovery for sitemaps through `robots.txt`.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] In May 2007, the state governments of Arizona, California, Utah and Virginia announced they would use Sitemaps on their web sites.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] The Sitemaps protocol is based on ideas from "Crawler-friendly Web Servers," with improvements including auto-discovery through `robots.txt` and the ability to specify the priority and change frequency of pages.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] The Sitemap Protocol format consists of XML tags.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Sitemaps can also be just a plain text list of URLs.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] They can also be compressed in .gz format.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] A sample Sitemap that contains just one URL and uses all optional tags is shown below.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Support for the elements that are not required can vary from one search engine to another.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Google ignores `<priority>`and `<changefreq>` values.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] The Sitemaps protocol allows the Sitemap to be a simple list of URLs in a text file.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] The file specifications of XML Sitemaps apply to text Sitemaps as well; the file must be UTF-8 encoded, and cannot be more than 50MiB (uncompressed) or contain more than 50,000 URLs.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Sitemaps that exceed these limits should be broken up into multiple sitemaps with a sitemap index file (a file that points to multiple sitemaps).
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] A syndication feed is a permitted method of submitting URLs to crawlers; this is advised mainly for sites that already have syndication feeds.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] One stated drawback is this method might only provide crawlers with more recently created URLs, but other URLs can still be discovered during normal crawling.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] It can be beneficial to have a syndication feed as a delta update (containing only the newest content) to supplement a complete sitemap.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] If Sitemaps are submitted directly to a search engine (pinged), it will return status information and any processing errors.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] The details involved with submission will vary with the different search engines.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] This directive is independent of the user-agent line, so it doesn't matter where it is placed in the file.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] If the website has several sitemaps, multiple "Sitemap:" records may be included in `robots.txt`, or the URL can simply point to the main sitemap index file.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Sitemap URLs submitted using the sitemap submission URLs need to be URL-encoded, for example: replace `:` (colon) with `%3A`, replace `/` (slash) with `%2F`.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Google retired sitemap submissions using URLs in late 2023.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Sitemaps supplement and do not replace the existing crawl-based mechanisms that search engines already use to discover URLs.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Using this protocol does not guarantee that web pages will be included in search indexes, nor does it influence the way that pages are ranked in search results.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] The Sitemap XML protocol is also extended to provide a way of listing multiple Sitemaps in a **sitemap index** file.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] The maximum sitemap size of 50 MiB (uncompressed) or 50,000 URLs means this is necessary for large sites.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] An example of sitemap index referencing one separate sitemap follows.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Sitemaps can be compressed using gzip, reducing bandwidth consumption.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Multiple sitemap files are supported, with a Sitemap index file serving as an entry point.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Sitemap index files may not list more than 50,000 Sitemaps and must be no larger than 50MiB and can be compressed.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] You can have more than one Sitemap index file.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] According to Google, a single property in Google Search Console can include up to 500 sitemap index files.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Additionally, sitemaps that are referenced in a sitemap index file must be located in the same directory as the sitemap index file, or in a subdirectory lower in the site hierarchy.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Best practice for optimising a sitemap index for search engine crawlability is to ensure the index refers only to sitemaps as opposed to other sitemap indexes; nesting a sitemap index within a sitemap index is invalid according to Google.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] A number of additional XML sitemap types outside of the scope of the Sitemaps protocol are supported by Google to allow webmasters to provide additional data on the content of their websites.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Video and image sitemaps are intended to improve the capability of websites to rank in image and video searches.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Video sitemaps indicate data related to embedding and autoplaying, preferred thumbnails to show in search results, publication date, video duration, and other metadata.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Video sitemaps are also used to allow search engines to index videos that are embedded on a website, but that are hosted externally, such as on Vimeo or YouTube.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Image sitemaps are used to indicate image metadata, such as licensing information, geographic location, and an image's caption.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Google supports a Google News sitemap type for facilitating quick indexing of time-sensitive news subjects.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] In December 2011, Google announced the annotations for sites that want to target users in many languages and, optionally, countries.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] A few months later Google announced, on their official blog, that they are adding support for specifying the rel="alternate" and hreflang annotations in Sitemaps.
[src:sitemap-xml/sitemaps] Instead of the (until then only option) HTML link elements the Sitemaps option offered many advantages which included a smaller page size and easier deployment for some websites.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A **web crawler**, sometimes called a **spider** or **spiderbot** and often shortened to **crawler**, is an Internet bot that systematically browses the World Wide Web and that is typically operated by search engines for the purpose of Web indexing (*web spidering*).
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Web search engines and some other websites use web crawling or spidering software to update their web content or indices of other sites' web content.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Web crawlers copy pages for processing by a search engine, which indexes the downloaded pages so that users can search more efficiently.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Crawlers consume resources on visited systems and often visit sites unprompted.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Issues of schedule, load, and "politeness" come into play when large collections of pages are accessed.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Mechanisms exist for public sites not wishing to be crawled to make this known to the crawling agent.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] For example, including a `robots.txt` file can request bots to index only parts of a website, or nothing at all.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The number of web pages is extremely large, and search engines do not index all web content.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Studies of late-1990s search engines found that individual engines indexed only a fraction of the then-indexable web.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Modern search engines use crawling, indexing, and ranking systems to return relevant results quickly, although not all pages are crawled, indexed, or served.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Crawlers can validate hyperlinks and HTML code.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] They can also be used for web scraping and data-driven programming.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A web crawler is also known as a *spider*, an *ant*, an *automatic indexer*, or (in the FOAF software context) a *Web scutter*.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A web crawler starts with a list of URLs to visit.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Those first URLs are called the *seeds*.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] As the crawler visits these URLs, by communicating with web servers that respond to those URLs, it identifies all the hyperlinks in the retrieved web pages and adds them to the list of URLs to visit, called the *crawl frontier*.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] URLs from the frontier are recursively visited according to a set of policies.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] If the crawler is performing archiving of websites (or web archiving), it copies and saves the information as it goes.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The archives are usually stored in such a way they can be viewed, read and navigated as if they were on the live web, but are preserved as 'snapshots'.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The large volume implies the crawler can only download a limited number of the Web pages within a given time, so it needs to prioritize its downloads.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The high rate of change can imply the pages might have already been updated or even deleted.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The number of possible URLs crawled being generated by server-side software has also made it difficult for web crawlers to avoid retrieving duplicate content.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Endless combinations of HTTP GET (URL-based) parameters exist, of which only a small selection will actually return unique content.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] For example, a simple online photo gallery may offer three options to users, as specified through HTTP GET parameters in the URL.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] If there exist four ways to sort images, three choices of thumbnail size, two file formats, and an option to disable user-provided content, then the same set of content can be accessed with 48 different URLs, all of which may be linked on the site.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] This mathematical combination creates a problem for crawlers, as they must sort through endless combinations of relatively minor scripted changes in order to retrieve unique content.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Given the current size of the Web, even large search engines cover only a portion of the publicly available part.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A 2009 study showed even large-scale search engines index no more than 40–70% of the indexable Web; a previous study by Steve Lawrence and Lee Giles showed that no search engine indexed more than 16% of the Web in 1999.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] As a crawler always downloads just a fraction of the Web pages, it is highly desirable for the downloaded fraction to contain the most relevant pages and not just a random sample of the Web.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] This requires a metric of importance for prioritizing Web pages.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The importance of a page is a function of its intrinsic quality, its popularity in terms of links or visits, and even of its URL (the latter is the case of vertical search engines restricted to a single top-level domain, or search engines restricted to a fixed Web site).
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Designing a good selection policy has an added difficulty: it must work with partial information, as the complete set of Web pages is not known during crawling.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Junghoo Cho *et al.* made the first study on policies for crawling scheduling.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Their data set was a 180,000-pages crawl from the stanford.edu domain, in which a crawling simulation was done with different strategies.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The ordering metrics tested were breadth-first, backlink count and partial PageRank calculations.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] One of the conclusions was that if the crawler wants to download pages with high Pagerank early during the crawling process, then the partial Pagerank strategy is the better, followed by breadth-first and backlink-count.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] However, these results are for just a single domain.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Cho also wrote his PhD dissertation at Stanford on web crawling.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Marc Najork and Janet Wiener performed an actual crawl on 328 million pages, using breadth-first ordering.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] They found that a breadth-first crawl captures pages with high Pagerank early in the crawl (but they did not compare this strategy against other strategies).
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Abiteboul designed a crawling strategy based on an algorithm called OPIC (On-line Page Importance Computation).
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] In OPIC, each page is given an initial sum of "cash" that is distributed equally among the pages it points to.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] It is similar to a PageRank computation, but it is faster and is only done in one step.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] An OPIC-driven crawler downloads first the pages in the crawling frontier with higher amounts of "cash".
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Experiments were carried in a 100,000-pages synthetic graph with a power-law distribution of in-links.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] However, there was no comparison with other strategies nor experiments in the real Web.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Boldi *et al.* used simulation on subsets of the Web of 40 million pages from the .it domain and 100 million pages from the WebBase crawl, testing breadth-first against depth-first, random ordering and an omniscient strategy.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The comparison was based on how well PageRank computed on a partial crawl approximates the true PageRank value.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Some visits that accumulate PageRank very quickly (most notably, breadth-first and the omniscient visit) provide very poor progressive approximations.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Baeza-Yates *et al.* used simulation on two subsets of the Web of 3 million pages from the .gr and .cl domain, testing several crawling strategies.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] They showed that both the OPIC strategy and a strategy that uses the length of the per-site queues are better than breadth-first crawling, and that it is also very effective to use a previous crawl, when it is available, to guide the current one.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Daneshpajouh *et al.* designed a community based algorithm for discovering good seeds.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Their method crawls web pages with high PageRank from different communities in less iteration in comparison with crawl starting from random seeds.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] One can extract good seed from a previously-crawled-Web graph using this new method.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Using these seeds, a new crawl can be very effective.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A crawler may only want to seek out HTML pages and avoid all other MIME types.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] In order to request only HTML resources, a crawler may make an HTTP HEAD request to determine a Web resource's MIME type before requesting the entire resource with a GET request.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] To avoid making numerous HEAD requests, a crawler may examine the URL and only request a resource if the URL ends with certain characters such as .html, .htm, .asp, .aspx, .php, .jsp, .jspx or a slash.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] This strategy may cause numerous HTML Web resources to be unintentionally skipped.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Some crawlers may also avoid requesting any resources that have a "?" in them (are dynamically produced) in order to avoid spider traps that may cause the crawler to download an infinite number of URLs from a Web site.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] This strategy is unreliable if the site uses URL rewriting to simplify its URLs.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Website owners may instruct crawlers on what resources they are allowed and forbidden to request with the robots.txt file.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A crawler can then use that information to chose what links to follow and which to avoid.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Crawlers usually perform some type of URL normalization in order to avoid crawling the same resource more than once.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The term *URL normalization*, also called *URL canonicalization*, refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] There are several types of normalization that may be performed including conversion of URLs to lowercase, removal of "." and ".." segments, and adding trailing slashes to the non-empty path component.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Some crawlers intend to download/upload as many resources as possible from a particular web site.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] So *path-ascending crawler* was introduced that would ascend to every path in each URL that it intends to crawl.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] For example, when given a seed URL of http://llama.org/hamster/monkey/page.html, it will attempt to crawl /hamster/monkey/, /hamster/, and /.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Cothey found that a path-ascending crawler was very effective in finding isolated resources, or resources for which no inbound link would have been found in regular crawling.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The importance of a page for a crawler can also be expressed as a function of the similarity of a page to a given query. web crawlers that attempt to download pages that are similar to each other are called **focused crawler** or **topical crawlers**.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The main problem in focused crawling is that in the context of a web crawler, we would like to be able to predict the similarity of the text of a given page to the query before actually downloading the page.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A possible predictor is the anchor text of links; this was the approach taken by Pinkerton in the first web crawler of the early days of the Web.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Diligenti *et al.* propose using the complete content of the pages already visited to infer the similarity between the driving query and the pages that have not been visited yet.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The performance of a focused crawling depends mostly on the richness of links in the specific topic being searched, and a focused crawling usually relies on a general Web search engine for providing starting points.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] An example of the focused crawlers are academic crawlers, which crawls free-access academic related documents, such as the *citeseerxbot*, which is the crawler of CiteSeerX search engine.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Other academic search engines are Google Scholar and Microsoft Academic Search etc.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Because most academic papers are published in PDF formats, such kind of crawler is particularly interested in crawling PDF, PostScript files, Microsoft Word including their zipped formats.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Because of this, general open-source crawlers, such as Heritrix, must be customized to filter out other MIME types, or a middleware is used to extract these documents out and import them to the focused crawl database and repository.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Identifying whether these documents are academic or not is challenging and can add a significant overhead to the crawling process, so this is performed as a post crawling process using machine learning or regular expression algorithms.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] These academic documents are usually obtained from home pages of faculties and students or from publication page of research institutes.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Because academic documents make up only a small fraction of all web pages, a good seed selection is important in boosting the efficiencies of these web crawlers.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Other academic crawlers may download plain text and HTML files, that contains metadata of academic papers, such as titles, papers, and abstracts.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] This increases the overall number of papers, but a significant fraction may not provide free PDF downloads.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Another type of focused crawlers is semantic focused crawler, which makes use of domain ontologies to represent topical maps and link Web pages with relevant ontological concepts for the selection and categorization purposes.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] In addition, ontologies can be automatically updated in the crawling process.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Dong et al. introduced such an ontology-learning-based crawler using a support-vector machine to update the content of ontological concepts when crawling Web pages.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The Web has a very dynamic nature, and crawling a fraction of the Web can take weeks or months.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] By the time a web crawler has finished its crawl, many events could have happened, including creations, updates, and deletions.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] From the search engine's point of view, there is a cost associated with not detecting an event, and thus having an outdated copy of a resource.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The most-used cost functions are freshness and age.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Coffman *et al.* worked with a definition of the objective of a web crawler that is equivalent to freshness, but use a different wording: they propose that a crawler must minimize the fraction of time pages remain outdated.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] They also noted that the problem of web crawling can be modeled as a multiple-queue, single-server polling system, on which the web crawler is the server and the Web sites are the queues.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Page modifications are the arrival of the customers, and switch-over times are the interval between page accesses to a single Web site.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Under this model, mean waiting time for a customer in the polling system is equivalent to the average age for the web crawler.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The objective of the crawler is to keep the average freshness of pages in its collection as high as possible, or to keep the average age of pages as low as possible.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] These objectives are not equivalent: in the first case, the crawler is just concerned with how many pages are outdated, while in the second case, the crawler is concerned with how old the local copies of pages are.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] In both cases, the repeated crawling order of pages can be done either in a random or a fixed order.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Cho and Garcia-Molina proved the surprising result that, in terms of average freshness, the uniform policy outperforms the proportional policy in both a simulated Web and a real web crawl.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] In other words, a proportional policy allocates more resources to crawling frequently updating pages, but experiences less overall freshness time from them.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] To improve freshness, the crawler should penalize the elements that change too often.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The optimal re-visiting policy is neither the uniform policy nor the proportional policy.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The optimal method for keeping average freshness high includes ignoring the pages that change too often, and the optimal for keeping average age low is to use access frequencies that monotonically (and sub-linearly) increase with the rate of change of each page.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] In both cases, the optimal is closer to the uniform policy than to the proportional policy: as Coffman *et al.* note, "in order to minimize the expected obsolescence time, the accesses to any particular page should be kept as evenly spaced as possible".
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Explicit formulas for the re-visit policy are not attainable in general, but they are obtained numerically, as they depend on the distribution of page changes.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Cho and Garcia-Molina show that the exponential distribution is a good fit for describing page changes, while Ipeirotis *et al.* show how to use statistical tools to discover parameters that affect this distribution.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The re-visiting policies considered here regard all pages as homogeneous in terms of quality ("all pages on the Web are worth the same"), something that is not a realistic scenario, so further information about the Web page quality should be included to achieve a better crawling policy.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Crawlers can retrieve data much quicker and in greater depth than human searchers, so they can have a crippling impact on the performance of a site.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] If a single crawler is performing multiple requests per second and/or downloading large files, a server can have a hard time keeping up with requests from multiple crawlers.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] As noted by Koster, the use of web crawlers is useful for a number of tasks, but comes with a price for the general community.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A partial solution to these problems is the robots exclusion protocol, also known as the robots.txt protocol that is a standard for administrators to indicate which parts of their Web servers should not be accessed by crawlers.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] This standard does not include a suggestion for the interval of visits to the same server, even though this interval is the most effective way of avoiding server overload.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Recently commercial search engines like Google, Ask Jeeves, MSN and Yahoo!
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Search are able to use an extra "Crawl-delay:" parameter in the robots.txt file to indicate the number of seconds to delay between requests.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The first proposed interval between successive page loads was 60 seconds.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Cho uses 10 seconds as an interval for accesses, and the WIRE crawler uses 15 seconds as the default.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The MercatorWeb crawler follows an adaptive politeness policy: if it took *t* seconds to download a document from a given server, the crawler waits for 10*t* seconds before downloading the next page.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] For those using web crawlers for research purposes, a more detailed cost-benefit analysis is needed and ethical considerations should be taken into account when deciding where to crawl and how fast to crawl.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Anecdotal evidence from access logs shows that access intervals from known crawlers vary between 20 seconds and 3–4 minutes.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] It is worth noticing that even when being very polite, and taking all the safeguards to avoid overloading Web servers, some complaints from Web server administrators are received.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Sergey Brin and Larry Page noted in 1998, "... running a crawler which connects to more than half a million servers ... generates a fair amount of e-mail and phone calls.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A parallel crawler is a crawler that runs multiple processes in parallel.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The goal is to maximize the download rate while minimizing the overhead from parallelization and to avoid repeated downloads of the same page.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] To avoid downloading the same page more than once, the crawling system requires a policy for assigning the new URLs discovered during the crawling process, as the same URL can be found by two different crawling processes.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A crawler must not only have a good crawling strategy, as noted in the previous sections, but it should also have a highly optimized architecture.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Web crawlers are a central part of search engines, and details on their algorithms and architecture are kept as business secrets.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] When crawler designs are published, there is often an important lack of detail that prevents others from reproducing the work.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] There are also emerging concerns about "search engine spamming", which prevent major search engines from publishing their ranking algorithms.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Web crawlers typically identify themselves to a Web server by using the User-agent field of an HTTP request.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Web site administrators typically examine their Web servers' log and use the user agent field to determine which crawlers have visited the web server and how often.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The user agent field may include a URL where the Web site administrator may find out more information about the crawler.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Examining Web server log is tedious task, and therefore some administrators use tools to identify, track and verify web crawlers.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Spambots and other malicious web crawlers are unlikely to place identifying information in the user agent field, or they may mask their identity as a browser or other well-known crawler.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Web site administrators prefer web crawlers to identify themselves so that they can contact the owner if needed.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] In some cases, crawlers may be accidentally trapped in a crawler trap or they may be overloading a Web server with requests, and the owner needs to stop the crawler.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Identification is also useful for administrators that are interested in knowing when they may expect their Web pages to be indexed by a particular search engine.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] A vast amount of web pages lie in the deep or invisible web.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] These pages are typically only accessible by submitting queries to a database, and regular crawlers are unable to find these pages if there are no links that point to them.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Google's Sitemaps protocol and mod oai are intended to allow discovery of these deep-Web resources.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Deep web crawling also multiplies the number of web links to be crawled.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Some crawlers only take some of the URLs in `<a href="URL">` form.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] In some cases, such as the Googlebot, web crawling is done on all text contained inside the hypertext content, tags, or text.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Strategic approaches may be taken to target deep Web content.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] With a technique called screen scraping, specialized software may be customized to automatically and repeatedly query a given Web form with the intention of aggregating the resulting data.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Such software can be used to span multiple Web forms across multiple Websites.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Data extracted from the results of one Web form submission can be taken and applied as input to another Web form thus establishing continuity across the Deep Web in a way not possible with traditional web crawlers.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Pages built on AJAX are among those causing problems to web crawlers.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] Google has proposed a format of AJAX calls that their bot can recognize and index.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] There are a number of "visual web scraper/crawler" products available on the web which will crawl pages and structure data into columns and rows based on the users requirements.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] One of the main difference between a classic and a visual crawler is the level of programming ability required to set up a crawler.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The latest generation of "visual scrapers" remove the majority of the programming skill needed to be able to program and start a crawl to scrape web data.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The visual scraping/crawling method relies on the user "teaching" a piece of crawler technology, which then follows patterns in semi-structured data sources.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] The dominant method for teaching a visual crawler is by highlighting data in a browser and training columns and rows.
[src:sitemap-xml/web-crawler] While the technology is not new, for example it was the basis of Needlebase which has been bought by Google (as part of a larger acquisition of ITA Labs), there is continued growth and investment in this area by investors and end-users.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:sitemap-xml/xml] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
